	affiliations = {National Research Institute of Science and Technology for Environment and Agriculture (INRAE), Paris, France; Govind Ballabh Pant University of Agriculture and Technology (GBPUAT), Uttarakhand, Pantnagar, India; University of California-Davis, Davis, CA, United States; Penn State University, United States; Government of West Australia, Australia; Graphic Era University, India; ETH Zürich, Switzerland; University of Reading, United Kingdom; University of Twente, Netherlands; Cornell University, United States; Università Cattolica Del Sacro Cuore, Italy; World Vegetable Center, Thailand; Swedish University of Agricultural Sciences, Sweden; National Institute of Agricultural Botany, East Malling Research Station (NIAB EMR), United Kingdom; North Carolina State University, United States; Ohio State University, United States; Universidade Federal de Viçosa, Brazil; Biotrigo Genética, Brazil; Universidad de Buenos Aires, Argentina; U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA), United States; Washington State University, United States; Chinese Academy of Agricultural Sciences, China; Northwest A&F University, China; Universitas Sumatera Utara, Indonesia; International Rice Research Institute, Philippines; Can Tho University, Viet Nam; China Agricultural University, China; International Institute of Tropical Agriculture (IITA), Nigeria; University of Florida, United States; International Potato Center (CIP), Peru; Instituto de Investigaciones Agropecuarias, Chile; Wageningen University and Research, Netherlands; SASA, United Kingdom; TUM School of Life Sciences, Germany; IITA, Tanzania; IITA, Cameroon; IITA, Kenya; Stellenbosch University, South Africa; National Agricultural Research Organization (NARO), Uganda; Instituto Agroforestal Mediterráneo, Universitat Politècnica de València, Spain; CNR, Istituto per la Protezione Sostenibile Delle Piante, Italy; USDA-ARS, United States; Citrus Research and Education Center, University of Florida, United States; Cornell AgriTech, United States; CIRAD, France; Centro de Citricultura, Instituto Agronômico, Brazil; Instituto Valenciano de Investigaciones Agrarias, Spain; The University of Queensland, Australia; Citrus Research International, South Africa; Southwest University, China; World Vegetable Center, Ethiopia; World Vegetable Center, Taiwan; National Research Council of Italy, Italy; Plante & Cité, France; Forest Research, United Kingdom; U.S. Forest Service, Pacific Southwest Research Station, Albany, CA, United States; U.S. Forest Service, Northern Research Station, St. Paul, MN, United States; BC Ministry of Forests, Canada; USDA Forest Service, United States; Weyerhaeuser Company, United States; Natural Resources Canada, Canada; Department of Primary Industries, Australia; Parks and Wildlife Service, Department of Biodiversity, Conservation and Attractions, WA, Australia; Australian Network for Plant Conservation, Australia; Murdoch University, Australia; University of Arizona, United States; University of Utah, United States; Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute, United States; University of South Florida, United States},
	abstract = {The Global Plant Health Assessment (GPHA) is a collective, volunteer-based effort to assemble expert opinions on plant health and disease impacts on ecosystem services based on published scientific evidence. The GPHA considers a range of forest, agricultural, and urban systems worldwide. These are referred to as (Ecoregion × Plant System), i.e., selected case examples involving keystone plants in given parts of the world. The GPHA focuses on infectious plant diseases and plant pathogens, but encompasses the abiotic (e.g., temperature, drought, and floods) and other biotic (e.g., animal pests and humans) factors associated with plant health. Among the 33 (Ecoregion × Plant System) considered, 18 are assessed as in fair or poor health, and 20 as in declining health. Much of the observed state of plant health and its trends are driven by a combination of forces, including climate change, species invasions, and human management. Healthy plants ensure (i) provisioning (food, fiber, and material), (ii) regulation (climate, atmosphere, water, and soils), and (iii) cultural (recreation, inspiration, and spiritual) ecosystem services. All these roles that plants play are threatened by plant diseases. Nearly none of these three ecosystem services are assessed as improving. Results indicate that the poor state of plant health in sub-Saharan Africa gravely contributes to food insecurity and environmental degradation. Results further call for the need to improve crop health to ensure food security in the most populated parts of the world, such as in South Asia, where the poorest of the poor, the landless farmers, are at the greatest risk. The overview of results generated from this work identifies directions for future research to be championed by a new generation of scientists and revived public extension services. Breakthroughs from science are needed to (i) gather more data on plant health and its consequences, (ii) identify collective actions to manage plant systems, (iii) exploit the phytobiome diversity in breeding programs, (iv) breed for plant genotypes with resilience to biotic and abiotic stresses, and (v) design and implement plant systems involving the diversity required to ensure their adaptation to current and growing challenges, including climate change and pathogen invasions. © 2023 The American Phytopathological Society.},
	author_keywords = {biodiversity; climate change; food security; global population; plant diseases; sustainability},
